Java Architecture & Design Document – Modular Monolith MVP

1. Overview

This document describes the Java backend architecture for the multi-tenant platform, including:
	•	Architectural style and patterns
	•	Module boundaries and dependencies
	•	Design patterns used per layer
	•	Folder / package structure (filesystem)
	•	Communication patterns (APIs + internal events)
	•	Cross-cutting concerns (auth, tenancy, observability)

The backend is a modular monolith designed to evolve into microservices later.

⸻

2. Architectural Style

2.1 Modular Monolith (Option B)
	•	Single deployable Spring Boot application
	•	Clear module boundaries inside the codebase
	•	Modules communicate via:
	•	service interfaces
	•	internal domain events (after-commit)

2.2 Why this fits MVP
	•	Faster iteration and lower operational cost
	•	Strong boundaries reduce coupling
	•	Event model already aligns with future Kafka/outbox

⸻

3. High-Level System Context

3.1 External clients
	•	Public Site (Astro): reads public APIs for catalog + site content + checkout
	•	Merchant Admin (React SPA): uses authenticated APIs to manage catalog, orders, content, staff
	•	Payload CMS: content store only; accessed via Java Content Gateway
	•	Neon Postgres: primary database
	•	Cloudflare R2: product image storage
	•	Wompi: payment provider (tenant-owned accounts), webhook-driven confirmations

3.2 Public vs Admin API separation
	•	Public base: /api/public/v1/...
	•	Admin base: /api/v1/...

Tenant resolution:
	•	Public: Host header primary + tenantSlug fallback endpoints
	•	Admin: tenantId in path and token; must match

⸻

4. Module Map (Boundaries)

4.1 Core modules (MVP)
	•	tenancy: tenant resolution, TenantContext
	•	auth: users, memberships, login, refresh rotation, invites/reset
	•	policy: centralized authorization (roles → actions)
	•	store: products, categories, images (R2), linked products
	•	orders: order creation, fulfillment lifecycle, offline marking paid, refunds record
	•	payments: PaymentProvider abstraction, payment attempts, Wompi integration, webhooks
	•	content-gateway: safe allowlisted access to Payload for settings/pages
	•	observability: structured logging, trace IDs, metrics hooks
	•	events: internal event interfaces, after-commit publishing, consumption dedupe

4.2 Deferred modules
	•	domains: domain automation (deferred)
	•	scheduling: services/availability/bookings (deferred)

4.3 Dependency rule (enforced)
	•	Modules may depend on:
	•	shared kernel (common primitives)
	•	policy/auth/tenancy as cross-cutting
	•	Feature modules should not directly depend on each other’s persistence.
	•	Cross-module coordination uses:
	•	stable service interfaces
	•	events

⸻

5. Layered Architecture (per module)

Each module follows a conventional layered structure:
	•	controller (API)
	•	request validation
	•	maps DTO ↔ service calls
	•	never contains business rules
	•	service (application/domain orchestration)
	•	business workflows
	•	state transitions
	•	authorization checks via policy
	•	emits domain events (after commit)
	•	repository (data access)
	•	tenant-scoped queries
	•	returns domain models
	•	model (domain)
	•	entities / aggregates
	•	value objects
	•	enums for states
	•	dto (API contracts)
	•	request/response classes
	•	mapper
	•	DTO ↔ domain mapping
	•	events
	•	module event interfaces + event types
	•	config
	•	module configuration (beans, wiring)

