6. Core Architectural Patterns

6.1 Centralized Policy Authorization (Locked)
	•	One place defines allowed actions
	•	Roles map to actions
	•	Controllers/services call policy checks

Benefits:
	•	Consistent permissions across the system
	•	Easier to extend (new modules/actions)

6.2 Capability Gating
	•	Feature flags per tenant:
	•	CAP_STORE, CAP_SCHEDULING (future)
	•	Enforced in services and reflected in /me response

6.3 Domain State Machines
	•	Orders: fulfillment status separate from payment status
	•	Payments: payment attempts are authoritative

State transitions:
	•	Enforced in service layer within a DB transaction
	•	Invalid transitions → 409 conflict

6.4 Ports & Adapters (inside monolith)
	•	External systems accessed via interfaces:
	•	PaymentProvider
	•	PayloadClient
	•	ObjectStorageClient

Implementation can be swapped later (Kafka, different CMS, different storage).

⸻

7. Design Patterns Used

7.1 Factory
	•	PaymentProviderFactory selects provider implementation by tenant config

7.2 Strategy
	•	Provider-specific logic behind PaymentProvider interface

7.3 Adapter
	•	Payload integration via PayloadClient adapter
	•	R2 integration via ObjectStorageClient

7.4 Domain Events
	•	After-commit publish via module event interfaces
	•	Async consumers for side effects

7.5 Idempotency
	•	Idempotency keys for:
	•	payment attempt creation
	•	(optional) checkout order creation
	•	Webhook dedupe + consumption table for side effects

⸻

8. Internal Event Model (Now) → Kafka (Later)

8.1 Current (MVP)
	•	Per-module publisher interfaces
	•	After-commit publishing mandatory
	•	At-least-once semantics
	•	Idempotent handlers
	•	event_consumptions for side effects

8.2 Later
	•	Replace publishers with Kafka producers
	•	Add outbox when Kafka or guaranteed delivery is needed

⸻

9. Data Management

9.1 Single schema + module-owned migrations
	•	Liquibase SQL migrations
	•	One schema
	•	Module folders under db/changelog/<module>/...

9.2 Tenant isolation
	•	TenantContext derived from token
	•	All tenant-owned tables include tenant_id
	•	Repositories always filter by tenant_id

⸻

10. Observability

10.1 Logging
	•	JSON logs with MDC:
	•	traceId, tenantId, userId, service, env

10.2 Request IDs
	•	X-Trace-Id generated/propagated

10.3 Audit logs
	•	Postgres audit table records sensitive actions:
	•	mark paid, refunds, staff changes, payment settings

10.4 Metrics & dashboards
	•	Micrometer + Prometheus format
	•	Grafana Cloud free tier for dashboards/alerts/logs (MVP)

