12. API Package Separation

Controllers are grouped by API surface:
	•	Public controllers: /api/public/v1/...
	•	Admin controllers: /api/v1/...

Recommended:
	•	controller/public/
	•	controller/admin/

This reduces accidental auth mistakes.

⸻

13. Security Basics
	•	Strict CORS allowlist per environment
	•	No secrets in logs
	•	Webhooks verified by signature
	•	Rate limiting on public checkout endpoints via Cloudflare

⸻

14. Development Guidelines

14.1 Golden path tests (must have)
	•	Tenant isolation
	•	Auth refresh rotation
	•	Order state transitions
	•	Payment webhook idempotency

14.2 Feature development flow
	•	Add Liquibase migration
	•	Add repository + service + controller
	•	Add policy action checks
	•	Emit events after commit
	•	Add audit entry for sensitive actions
	•	Add tests

⸻

15. Summary

The Java backend uses a modular monolith with strict boundaries, centralized policy, after-commit internal events, and low-cost observability. It is intentionally designed to evolve to microservices/Kafka later without rework.

This document is architectural reference + implementation guide for starting development.